docs.abstract: In the wake of outrage over George Floyd’s death, several deadly episodes involving the police are receiving renewed attention.
docs.snippet: In the wake of outrage over George Floyd’s death, several deadly episodes involving the police are receiving renewed attention.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — The story of Elijah McClain’s death, which came after he was confronted and detained by police officers last year in the Denver suburb of Aurora, Colo., did not go unnoticed by residents and the local news media in the weeks that followed.

headline.main: Elijah McClain Died After He Was Detained. Now He’s Being Remembered.
headline.print_headline: Outrage Prompts New Scrutiny of Police Killings

byline.original: By Richard Fausset and Shaila Dewan

docs.abstract: Republicans have been startled by the extent to which public opinion has shifted in recent days after the killings of unarmed black Americans by the police and the protests that have followed.
docs.snippet: Republicans have been startled by the extent to which public opinion has shifted in recent days after the killings of unarmed black Americans by the police and the protests that have followed.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Congressional Republicans, caught flat-footed by an election-year groundswell of public support for overhauling policing in America to address systemic racism, are struggling to coalesce around a legislative response.

headline.main: G.O.P. Scrambles to Respond to Public Demands for Police Overhaul
headline.print_headline: G.O.P. Blindsided By Public’s Rage At Floyd Killing

docs.abstract: Hundreds joined a march in Taipei, making it one of the few places in the world to proceed with such an event during the coronavirus pandemic.

docs.lead_paragraph: TAIPEI, Taiwan — With the coronavirus pandemic making large gatherings impossible in many places, the biggest Pride events around the globe were mostly forced to scale back or move online.

headline.main: Taiwan Celebrates Pride With a Public Parade
headline.print_headline: Taiwan Celebrates L.G.B.T. Pride for a World Sidelined by a Pandemic

docs.abstract: As cultural institutions scramble to declare their support for Black Lives Matter, their gestures have felt both self-aggrandizing and too little too late.
docs.snippet: As cultural institutions scramble to declare their support for Black Lives Matter, their gestures have felt both self-aggrandizing and too little too late.
docs.lead_paragraph: The protests sparked by the public killing of George Floyd in police custody have added up, day by day, to a history-altering human rights movement, potentially the most consequential of the past 50 years. But they’ve left some of our history-writing and history-preserving institutions scrambling to find ways to join.

headline.main: Museums Are Finally Taking a Stand. But Can They Find Their Footing?
headline.print_headline: Museums Scramble to Catch Up With the Arc of History

docs.abstract: If he were to win in the Republican-leaning district in November, Dr. Webb, 37, would become the first black physician to have a vote in Congress. He will face an opponent who has had trouble fund-raising.

docs.lead_paragraph: Cameron Webb decisively won a four-way Democratic primary in Virginia on Tuesday, setting up a potentially competitive race in the state’s Fifth Congressional District, where the Republican incumbent was recently ousted in a drive-through convention.

headline.main: Virginia Democrats Pick Cameron Webb for a Seat They Think They Can Win Back
